.TH "PERFORMANCE.INTERACTIONCOUNT" "3JS" "January 14, 2026" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Performance.interactionCount \- Performance: interactionCount property
.SH SYNOPSIS
The read\-only \f[CR]performance.interactionCount\f[R] property
represents the number of real\-user interactions that have occurred on
the page since it was loaded.
.PP
Only discrete interactions with an \f[CR]interactionId\f[R] \(em such as
clicks and key events \(em are counted.
Other interactions, such as scroll interactions, are excluded.
.PP
This is useful when calculating Interaction to Next Paint (INP), and in
particular to exclude outliers for long\-lived pages.
INP takes the 98th percentile of interactions for a page and so excludes
1 in every 50 interactions as \(lqoutliers\(rq that are not reflective
of overall page responsiveness.
.SH VALUE
A number, which is initially \f[CR]0\f[R], and increments by
\f[CR]1\f[R] with each discrete interaction as measured by
\f[CR]PerformanceEventTiming\f[R], where an
\f[CR]PerformanceEventTiming.interactionId\f[R] is assigned.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Checking the number of interactions to accurately calculate INP
For pages with a large number of interactions, you can recalculate INP
after excluding 1 out of every 50 outliers using the following pattern:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]if\f[R] (performance.interactionCount >= 50) {
  recalculateINP(); \f[I]// Actual calculation is complex and is not shown here\f[R]
}
.EE
.SH SEE ALSO
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]PerformanceEventTiming\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]PerformanceEventTiming.interactionId\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
